            <div type="commentary">
                 <list type="witDetail">
                     <item n="1"><p>Also known as St Vigean's 6.</p>
                     </item>
                     <item n="2"><p>There is doubt over whether this is ogham or not. Combined with the brevity of the inscription, both its language and meaning cannot be readily determined.</p>
                     </item>
                     <item n="3"><p>The ogham inscription was originally recognised by Duke in 1887-8, who noted they were so defaced they were unintelligible (Geddes 2017, 184). Later, in 1903, Allen read it as a T-pattern (ibid). In 2005, Borland recognised the T-pattern but discerned two ogham letters 'RR' with a drawn stem-line (ibid). In Forsyth's view, the stem-line is questionable and the strength of the ogham strokes seem to be very similar to the other cuts on the face (ibid).</p>
                     </item>
                 </list>
            </div>
